<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12118a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12118a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12118a"> 118(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> S Columbanus v S Benedict</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">une r&egrave;gle qu&apos;il ne semble point avoir connue, commen&ccedil;ait &agrave; se propager en France. Elle avait pour auteur l&apos;italien Beno&icirc;t, ermite &agrave; Subiaco et fondateur du Mont-Cassin, mort en 543, et elle se distinguait &agrave; la fois par son caract&egrave;re positif, pratique et pond&eacute;r&eacute;: toutes choses qui manquaient aux constitutions columbanistes. Elle offrait le m&ecirc;me id&eacute;al de saintet&eacute; et d&apos;abn&eacute;gation; mais elle avait une tendre compassion pour l&apos;infirmit&eacute; de notre nature. Elle tenait le juste milieu entre la rigueur excessive qui exige trop, et la molle condescendance qui ne demande point assez, et surtout elle d&eacute;terminait, jusque dans les moindres d&eacute;tails, tout ce qui concernait l&apos;emploi des journ&eacute;es, la distribution des offices, l&apos;admission des novices, les v&oelig;ux, le gouvernement de la maison, la r&eacute;ception des h&ocirc;tes, etc. <br><font color="green">[one rule that he seems not to have known was beginning to spread in France. It was started by the Italian Benedict, a hermit in Subiaco and the founder of Monte Cassino, who died in 543. This rule is notable because it is simultaneously positive, practical, and moderate, traits that are absent in Columbanist constitutions. It offers the same ideal of saintliness and abnegation but it shows a tender compassion towards the infirmity of our nature. It occupies the middle ground between the excessive rigour that demands too much and the weak compliance that does not demand enough. Most of all it determines, down to the smallest detail, everything about the day&apos;s activities, the distribution of services, the admission of novices, the organisation of the household, the hosts&apos; reception, etc.]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 192</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
